                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d304">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">438.00/226: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The High Commissioner in Haiti</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Russell</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Port au Prince</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1923-03-26T09:00:00-05:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">March 26, 1923—9 a.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/>[Received 9:15 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>42. Department’s March 21, 6 [<hi rend="italic">5</hi>] p.m. President Borno
                    informs me he will telegraph to Monsieur Dejean today to accept French proposal
                    without reservation. He further stated that recourse to revision through
                    diplomatic channels would extend to other foreign governments having claims. His
                    interpretation is that if in proceedings of Claims Commission foreign delegate
                    files minority report disagreeing with other two delegates then the foreign
                    government [if it] so desires to [<hi rend="italic">may</hi>] take up claim
                    through diplomatic channels.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Russell</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
